<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / International Company News: Xerox shows 10% gain in net
profit to Dollars 128m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
XEROX, the US document-processing group, yesterday unveiled a 10 per cent
improvement in first-quarter net profits on a 3 per cent increase in
revenues.
Net income for the three months ended March 31 totalled Dollars 128m, or
Dollars 1.10 a fully diluted share, against Dollars 116m, or Dollars 1, in
last year's first quarter. Revenues were Dollars 3.31bn, compared with
Dollars 3.2bn.
Income from the group's document-processing business was Dollars 113m, up 3
per cent from the previous year. Revenues also rose 3 per cent to Dollars
3.3bn.
Mr Paul Allaire, chairman, said sales of less expensive copiers and
decentralised electronic printers continued to show strong growth worldwide.
However, the company's overall performance was hurt by the weak economic
climate in Japan and some parts of Europe.
During the latest quarter, Xerox cut about 1,000 jobs as part of the
company's previously announced plans to reduce its workforce by about 2,500.
Mr Allaire said the effect of the total reduction would be reflected in
Xerox's financial results later in the year.
Earnings from Xerox's insurance and financial services operations rose to
Dollars 66m in the quarter from Dollars 47m, though revenues dipped to
Dollars 944m from Dollars 1bn a year ago.
The company, which has been moving away from real estate and third-party
transactions, attributed the decline in revenues to strategic changes in
property and casualty insurance operations. Interest and headquarters
expenses rose to Dollars 51m from Dollars 41m, limiting earnings from
insurance and financial services to Dollars 15m against Dollars 6m last
year.
