<HEADLINE>
FT  28 APR 92 / Happier staff with profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAFF at the most profitable UK companies are significantly more satisfied
with their jobs than staff at less profitable companies.
The finding, part of a survey of 140,000 staff, conducted by International
Survey Research (ISR) at 55 companies, used 10 standard measures of
satisfaction. Staff at the most profitable companies were more satisfied on
every count. ISR believes staff satisfaction is necessary for profitability.
Mrs Rhiannon Chapman, director of the Industrial Society, the independent
body that promotes harmony at work, said: 'Staff feel more directly involved
in the business and therefore more able to contribute when they know how
their area of work affects profits. It may be that the most profitable
companies are more willing to give out that kind of information.'
Dr Adrian Furnham, a reader in psychology at London University, said the
survey did not show that staff satisfaction caused profits. 'It may be,
however, that the most profitable companies also have the best selection
procedures and select out the neurotics. There is a clear connection between
neurosis and work dissatisfaction.'
</TEXT>
