FT  28 APR 92 / Third world 'may set up trade blocs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEVELOPING countries cannot be expected to spend as much on environmental
protection as rich countries. They may also have to set up their own
regional trade blocs if the Uruguay Round trade liberalisation talks are not
concluded soon.
These warnings were delivered by Mr Alejandro Foxley, the Chilean finance
minister and chairman of the joint IMF/World Bank development committee,
whose meeting today is expected to focus mainly on trade and environmental
issues, ahead of the Earth Summit to be held in Rio de Janeiro this June.
He said poor countries were worried that industrialised nations would 'sneak
in' new protectionist barriers under the guise of tougher environmental
standards. Poor countries should be allowed to phase in environmental
controls over a long period.
On trade, Mr Foxley said developing countries were deeply disappointed that
their unilateral efforts to liberalise trade had elicited little response
from industrialised countries. Rich countries still spent Dollars 250bn
(Pounds 141.2bn) on agricultural protection, five times the amount of
development aid.
