<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / Guerrilla chiefs head for Kabul
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOUSEGO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFGHANISTAN'S new ruling council last night prepared to fly to Kabul, the
capital, today amid signs that guerrillas backing it had gained the upper
hand in fighting against mujahideen rivals.
Mr Sibghatullah Mojadidi, who has been charged with taking office at the
head of the 51-strong council, finally decided yesterday after a weekend of
fierce clashes that it was safe to head for Kabul from Peshawar, in
Pakistan. But by the time his party had arrived at the airport, in failing
light and deteriorating weather, it was too late to depart.
Mujahideen officials said Mr Mojadidi would leave this morning if the
situation in Kabul remained relatively calm.
Throughout yesterday Kabul echoed to the sound of automatic weapons and
artillery fire. Clashes erupted between forces loyal to Ahmed Shah Masood,
the Jamiat-i-Islami commander - who backs the new council  - and Gulbuddin
Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islam forces after Kabul fell to mujahideen fighters on
Saturday.
A Jamiat commander in the area of the Bala Hissar (old fort) said between 20
and 30 people had been killed there. The overall death toll was expected to
be much higher.
There was no telling last night whether Afghanistan would be plunged into a
fresh civil war after the end of the 13-year conflict between the Islamic
guerrillas and the communist regime.
Celebrations over a mujahideen victory turned to bloodshed as Pushtun
nationalists and Hezb guerrillas showed their determination to resist
domination of Kabul by non-Pushtun forces loyal to Mr Masood.
Mr Masood was appointed head of a six-man security committee by mujahideen
leaders in Peshawar on Saturday and given orders to secure the city. Three
of the other members were from his Jamiat party while two prominent Pushtuns
were also included. Pakistan yesterday supported the committee and new
ruling council.
Support by an overwhelming majority of the guerrilla groups as well as the
United Nations had given legitimacy to the council, Pakistan's foreign
ministry said.
Mr Mojadidi condemned the assault on Kabul by Mr Hekmatyar who ordered his
men into the city on Saturday after rejecting the council and the plan for
the transfer of power. Last night Hezb forces controlled key pockets of
Kabul, including the Ministry of the Interior.
Jamiat vehicles manned by heavily armed guerrillas patrolled the deserted
streets of the capital.
General Nabi Azimi, former head of the Kabul garrison who has been
co-operating with Mr Masood, called on the security forces to obey him. But
two other Pushtun nationalist generals - General Mohammad Rafi and General
Watangarn, the former minister of defence - were siding with the Hekmatyar
forces.
Reports and analysis, Page 3
</TEXT>
