<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / Labour seeks order in leadership race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR LABOUR party figures will seek to impose some order on the elements
of farce in the party's leadership contest by insisting at today's meeting
of Labour MPs that there will be no immediate change to the rules.
But the renewed claims about which of the candidates for leader and deputy
leader were on course to secure the necessary 55 signatures from Labour MPs
 -sparked by the weekend's confusion about the rules  - have fuelled the row
over demands that all candidates should be able to address their colleagues
before nominations close tomorrow.
The issue will come to a head at the same meeting, where the demands are
unlikely to be met.
Continuing disarray in the election process is dismaying Labour MPs who
believe it is damaging the party severely by highlighting ways in which
Labour is not fully democratic.
A letter, which was sent to candidates on Friday by Ms Joyce Gould, the
party's organisation director, suggested that if a first-choice candidate
did not secure enough nominations, the MP concerned could nominate a
second-choice candidate.
After consultations, which included Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, and
Mr Larry Whitty, general secretary, senior party officials said yesterday
that, in spite of what was in the letter, there had been no change to the
rules. An MP could change his or her mind about who to nominate at the last
minute, but could not send in two nominations.
In a television interview yesterday with Mr Brian Walden, Mr Bryan Gould, a
candidate for both the leadership and the deputy leadership, admitted that
his request for the rules to be clarified had prompted the letter. He
fiercely rejected the idea that this meant he had manipulated the rules and
insisted that he was confident of being nominated for both posts.
However, supporters of other contenders reacted angrily, saying the
clarification seemed intended to benefit Mr Gould.
Mr Ken Livingstone, the leadership candidate supported by the left-wing
Campaign Group, said there was 'clear evidence' that party officials and
perhaps some MPs had tried to influence which candidates would appear on the
ballot paper.
The general union TGWU is today expected to announce that it will conduct a
workplace ballot of its members to decide how to cast its vote.
However, the engineering union AEU reiterated its position yesterday that it
had no money left for a postal ballot and refused to countenance a workplace
ballot. The AEU's leadership strongly favours a looser link with the Labour
party and an end to the block vote.
</TEXT>
