<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / Tecs pressure Shephard on training policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT must decide whether its training priority for young people is
guaranteeing a place to everybody or offering quality training, Mrs Gillian
Shephard, the new employment secretary, has been told by the leaders of
training and enterprise councils.
G10, the group of Tec chairmen that represents the movement to the
government, made clear at its first meeting with Mrs Shephard that it wanted
to change its relationship with the government.
Before the general election, relations between Tecs and the Department of
Employment were soured after heated negotiations over funding for 1992-93.
The government has reduced funding for many of the programmes operated by
Tecs, including Youth Training and Employment Training, the scheme for
unemployed adults.
Tecs - not all of which have yet settled their budgets  - are obliged to
guarantee a training place to all young people who want one. This year many
are claiming that the quality of training will suffer because of the cuts.
Many fear they will be unable to guarantee training places to all young
people. Tecs want more freedom to tailor programmes at a local level.
According to a confidential memo of the meeting with Mrs Shephard, held 10
days ago, G10 said Tecs wanted to influence policy. It told Mrs Shephard
that the strength of Tecs was developing effective local initiatives.
G10 said the government should fund Investors in People, the Tec-operated
scheme to improve training for people in work. At present, Tecs have no
specific funds for the project. It is understood they want about Pounds 20m
to fund the plan.
The memo said the meeting was cordial. Mrs Shephard 'warmly endorsed' the
Tec concept and said she hoped they would be 're-invigorated'.
Lessons to be learnt, Page 13
