<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / TGWU to present shake-up plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TGWU general union will tomorrow announce the biggest shake-up in its
history as it attempts to overcome a deep organisational and financial
crisis.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU, Britain's largest union, will
announce the first findings of a management consultancy report by Klein &amp;
Co, the US-based union consultants, which is likely to recommend cutting
some of the 11 regions and reducing their financial and political autonomy.
The union's right wing, which has its power base in the regions, is ready to
accept the phasing-out of the smaller regions - probably the south coast,
east coast and north-east, all of which have fewer than 50,000 members. It
may, however, resist the challenge to the financial powers of the regions
that would come from centralising the payment of union dues.
Klein is also expected to recommend reducing the 14 trade groups, making
better use of the union's computers and introducing proper budgets and
financial planning. Some of those points may emerge at a later stage in the
consultancy exercise.
The central drive of the changes will be to roll back some of the legacy of
decentralisation left by Mr Frank Cousins and Mr Jack Jones, leaders in the
1960s and 1970s, who reacted against the centralised, authoritarian regime
of the 1940s and 1950s.
Mr Morris, who is backed by the dominant broad-left faction on the union
executive, wants to bring in the changes without reviving the political
in-fighting for which the union is well known. He will need to take further
tough rationalisation decisions - on top of the recent increase in union
dues - if the TGWU is to start breaking even.
The union expects to raise nearly Pounds 1m a month from the 18 per cent
increase in dues agreed in February.
But some TGWU officials say privately that the financial crisis is even
worse than the published estimates have so far revealed.
The union suffered a Pounds 10m deficit last year. Before the rise in
contributions, a deficit of Pounds 11.6m had been expected for this year.
Planned savings of Pounds 5m this year from rationalisation and job cuts
will thus have to go ahead.
</TEXT>
