<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / Local authorities head for first clash with Howard
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITIES are heading for their first clash with Mr Michael Howard,
the environment secretary, over a government decision which they say will
cost councils at least Pounds 60m in the current financial year, and Pounds
100m in 1993-94.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, chairman of the Labour-controlled Association of
Metropolitan Authorities, has written to Mr Howard seeking an urgent meeting
about plans to pay councils a lump sum for certain loan charges from the
start of October, instead of continuing with specific grants.
The Department of the Environment has consistently assured local authorities
that the commutation of the specific loan charge grants for some housing and
urban-programme spending into a lump sum would be financially neutral
overall.
Councils, however, argue that because the distribution of the grant is not
based on the debt charges actually faced, there are significant differences
between the amounts of grant some authorities will lose, and the charges
they will continue to face. For Manchester, for example, the change is
expected to mean an extra budgetary requirement of more than Pounds 1m in
1992-93. They are also concerned that the method of interest-rate
calculation disadvantages many councils.
Councillors warn that in the current year the sums might almost certainly be
found only by cuts in areas such as education and social services.
To try to avoid service cuts, the AMA will urge the government to relax the
'minium revenue provision' rules, which ensure that councils set aside a
certain amount each year for debt repayment, in order to bridge the gap
between the amount of grant lost and the loan charges they will face.
Local government officials were incensed that while councils are acutely
conscious of government limits on their budgets, civil servants played down
the issue at one meeting, saying it added only another couple of pounds to
poll-tax levels.
</TEXT>
