FT  27 APR 92 / Doubt over Russia's IFC entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EARLY Russian membership of the International Finance Corp (IFC), the World
Bank affiliate charged with promoting private-sector investment, has been
thrown into doubt by problems in the US administration, writes Peter Norman
in Washington.
Russia and the other 14 former Soviet republics have completed the
formalities to become members of the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank. But the US has so far not given the go-ahead to a limited
increase in the capital of the IFC that would allow Russia and other
republics to join the affiliate.
Russia and the republics will be able to join the World Bank as it had
sufficient unallocated shares to give Russia a 2.92 per cent of World Bank
capital and the former Soviet republics, including Russia, 5.25 per cent.
The IFC, however, only had about half the number of unissued shares required
to make the former Soviet states into members with the same shareholdings as
in the World Bank.
