<HEADLINE>
FT  27 APR 92 / Political asylum requests halved under tougher British
controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MARSH, European Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE number of people applying for political asylum in Britain has dropped by
more than half this year as tougher Home Office screening controls start to
bite.
Officials believe that the latest statistics suggest a significant
proportion of last year's record 44,743 applications for asylum may have
reflected bogus requests.
This is because people requesting asylum, most of whom are already in the
country, have been required since the end of last year to go in person to
the Home Office asylum division in Croydon, rather than apply by post.
Potential asylum seekers may also have been deterred from applying by
Britain's tougher public stance on the issue.
The fall is to an average 1,730 applications a month in the first three
months compared with an average 3,730 last year. It is in sharp contrast to
the experience of other European countries such as Germany which are
continuing to experience growing inflows.
A total of 35,000 foreigners applied for asylum in Germany alone in March.
Based on current trends, this is almost twice as many as are likely to
register in the UK during the whole of this year.
The Home Office figures are likely to take the heat out of the debate over
immigration when the much-criticised Asylum Bill is re-introduced for
parliamentary scrutiny after the Queen's Speech on May 6.
The government postponed the bill by withdrawing it from the committee stage
in the House of Lords two months ago. The legislation is due to be
resubmitted to parliament either in the summer or in the autumn. It will
embody amendments which were made during its passage through the Commons
this year.
The government and refugee organisations such as Amnesty International have
been pointing for months to the problem of multiple applications. Individual
foreigners have been completing several asylum forms in different names.
Asylum seekers receive social security benefits as soon as their application
form has been officially lodged, giving them the chance of fraudulently
drawing extra benefits.
The average time for an application to be processed has been 14 months,
longer if appeals are involved.
Amnesty International has criticised the government in the past for not
channelling more resources towards processing asylum applications.
The Home Office has responded by stepping up recruitment and training. The
asylum division now has 550 staff, compared with just 50 in 1988. It now
spends Pounds 10m a year on processing requests, against only Pounds 1.7m
two years ago.
Extra resources have allowed more rapid handling of outstanding
applications. Decisions were taken on a total of 6,329 applications in the
first three months of the year. The government, however, believes it will
still take several years to clear the backlog of around 60,000 undecided
asylum cases inherited from previous years.
Editorial comment, Page 12
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
