FT  27 APR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Horizon is devoted to 'Iceman', the body which was found last September by
German hikers on the border between Austria and Italy. Being the seventh
body found on the mountain that year, it was removed in a routine fashion
and only identified later as being 5,300 years old. Artefacts included a
flint knife, copper axe, yew bow, and 14 viburnum arrows. There is immense
excitement in the world of archaeology (8.10 BBC2). BBC1's new sitcom Side
By Side (8.30) sounds like another study of English class attitudes. Gareth
Hunt plays a successful plumber whose DIY home improvements, such as the
'Acropolis' in his garden, irritate his neighbour. Panorama reports on an
apparently chronic water shortage in southern Britain. The south has
suffered its lowest rainfall for 200 years. The programme asks whether
nature alone is to blame, and what can be done (9.30). Most of ITV's evening
is occupied by a two-hour drama about a jazz musician who turns detective
when he becomes involved in a murder mystery: The Jazz Detective runs for an
hour before News At 10 and an hour after.
