FT  27 APR 92 / Second poll for Austrian candidates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC FREY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rudolf Streicher won the first round in Austria's presidential elections
yesterday, confirming his status as front-runner to succeed President Kurt
Waldheim.
But Mr Streicher, the minister for transportation and candidate of the
Social Democratic party, failed to win a clear majority and will face the
runner-up, Mr Thomas Klestil of the conservative People's Party, in a
run-off on May 24.
With 98 per cent of the votes counted, Mr Streicher led Mr Klestil with 40.8
per cent to 37.1 per cent. Mrs Heide Schmidt, the candidate of the
right-wing Freedom Party, polled 16.4 per cent, and Mr Robert Jungk, of the
Green Party, received 5.7 per cent.
Mr Klestil, a career diplomat, did far better and Mr Streicher worse than
their respective parties in the last elections in 1990.
With the voting pattern of the supporters of Mrs Schmidt und Mr Jungk
difficult to predict, the outcome of the second round is still open.
