FT  25 APR 92 / Survey into Sunday shopping
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
About a million people in England and Wales visited a supermarket every
Sunday during March, and 2.8m people shopped on a Sunday at least once
during the month, according to a survey by Nielson market research. The
figure for February was 3m, and for January 2.6m.
London has the highest proportion of Sunday shoppers, at about 18 per cent.
 Households in the north of England are the least enthusiastic - only one in
ten Yorkshire-area households took advantage of Sunday opening.
People spend more on Sundays.  The average shopping basket on Sundays in
1992 cost pounds 10, but the average bill on other days of the week was
pounds 7.40.
