<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 92 / Finance &amp; the Family: CGT allowances for March
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TABLE shows capital gains tax allowances for assets sold in March. To
use it, multiply the original cost of the assest by the figure shown for the
month in which you bought them.
If you subtract the result from the proceeds of your sale, the difference
will be your taxable gain or loss.
Suppose that you bought shares for pounds 6,000 in February 1986 and sold
them in March 1992 for pounds 13,500. Multiplying the original cost by the
February 1986 figure of 1.415 gives a total of pounds 8,490.
Subtracting that from the proceeds of pounds 13,500 gives a gain for tax
purposes of pounds 5,010 - below the 1991-92 pounds 5,500 CGT allowance. If
you realised no other gains during the year, the profit should be tax-free.
If you are selling shares bought before April 6, 1982, use the March 1982
figure.
