FT  25 APR 92 / City of London boundaries widen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SIGNIFICANT extensions to the boundaries of the City Corporation
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the local authority for the 'square mile' of the City of London - were
announced by the Local Government Boundary Commission yesterday.
London borough boundaries are under review as part of the Boundary
Commission's programme. The corporation, Britain's smallest local authority
with 5,000 residents sandwiched between seven inner London boroughs,
includes most of the City's old business district. The changes will add
about 1,000 to its residential population.
Notable additions to the City are the Golden Lane housing estate, north of
the Barbican; the entire Broadgate development, beside Liverpool Street
station; Milton Court, off Chiswell Street; and a large business district
east of Chancery Lane, including the Public Records Office. The only notable
loss is an area on Bishopsgate fronting the Spitalfields development.
Welcoming the extensions, Mr Michael Cassidy, chairman of the corporation's
policy committee, said: 'This will simplify the preparation, implementation
and monitoring of appropriate planning policies for the world's principal
financial centre.'
The corporation was under threat of abolition by Labour, but with the
Tories' re-election its future appears secure.
